[[Posttraumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD) is an anxiety disorder that may result from an individual experiencing a tragic, catastrophic, or traumatic event. Because of large benefits available to individuals with PTSD, the [[malingering]] of PTSD is a potential problem.

==Motivation==
Individuals who malinger PTSD may have several motivations for doing so. First, financial incentives are common. For example, the Department of Veterans Affairs offers substantial annual financial compensation to U.S. veterans who can prove that they suffer from PTSD related to their military service. This potential compensation can create an incentive for veterans to malinger PTSD.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Frueh, B. C., Grubaugh, A. L., Elhai, J. D., & Buckley, T. C.|title=US Department of Veterans Affairs disability policies for posttraumatic stress disorder: Administrative trends and implications for treatment, rehabilitation, and research |journal=British Journal of Psychiatry |volume=97|pages=U2143-2145 |doi=10.2105/AJPH.2007.115436}}</ref> Furthermore, the U.S. Social Security Administration offers social security disability payments to individuals documenting a disorder such as PTSD that impedes their ability to work, which additionally provides an incentive to malinger PTSD.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Taylor, S., Frueh, B. C., & Asmundson, G. J. G. |title=Detection and management of malingering in people presenting for treatment of posttraumatic stress disorder: Methods, obstacles, and recommendations | journal=Journal of Anxiety Disorders| volume=21|pages=22–41 |doi=10.1016/j.janxdis.2006.03.016}}</ref> Additionally, the potential for workers compensation can motivate individuals reporting a traumatic event at their workplace to fabricate PTSD; and finally the potential for personal injury lawsuits can motivate someone to malinger PTSD and sue an individual for causing PTSD as a result of attack, accident or other stressor.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Guriel, J., & Fremouw, W. |title=Assessing malingered posttraumatic stress disorder: A critical review |journal=Clinical Psychology Review| volume=23 |pages=881–904 |doi=10.1016/j.cpr.2003.07.001}}</ref>

Some individuals are known to malinger PTSD to obtain inpatient hospital treatment.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Salloway, S., Southwick, S., & Sadowsky, M.  |title=Opiate withdrawal presenting as posttraumatic stress disorder |journal=Hospital and Community Psychiatry |volume=41 |pages=666–667 |url=http://ps.psychiatryonline.org/cgi/content/citation/41/6/666}}</ref> Persons charged in criminal law cases are motivated to malinger PTSD in order to offset criminal responsibility for the crime and/or mitigate the associated penalties.<ref>{{cite book|editor=R. Rogers| title=Clinical assessment of malingering and deception|year=2008|publisher=Guilford Press.|last=Resnick, P. J., West, S., & Payne, J. W.|chapter=Malingering of posttraumatic disorders|edition=3rd|pages=109–127|ISBN=978-1-59385-699-1}}</ref> Some individuals are motivated to malinger PTSD (e.g., related to combat) in order to gain honor and recognition from others.<ref>{{cite book|last=Burkett, B. G., & Whitley, G.|title=Stolen valor: How the Vietnam generation was robbed of its heroes and history|year=1998|publisher=Verity Press|isbn=978-0-9667036-0-3}}</ref>

==Psychological assessment findings==
The [[Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory]]-2 (MMPI-2) is the most widely used psychological assessment measure that has been used in research to detect malingered PTSD, typically by comparing genuine PTSD patients with individuals trained and instructed to fabricate PTSD on the MMPI-2.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Demakis, G. J., & Elhai, J. D.  |title=Neuropsychological and psychological aspects of malingered posttraumatic stress disorder |journal=Psychological Injury and Law| volume=4 |pages=24–31 |doi=10.1007/s12207-011-9099-y}}</ref> Numerous studies using the MMPI-2 have demonstrated a moderately accurate ability to detect simulated PTSD.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Elhai, J. D., Gold, S. N., Sellers, A. H., & Dorfman, W. I. |title=The detection of malingered posttraumatic stress disorder with MMPI-2 fake bad indices |journal=Assessment| volume=8 |pages=221–236 |doi=10.1177/107319110100800210 |pmid=11428701}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Elhai, J. D., Gold, P. B., Frueh, B. C., & Gold, S. N. |title=Cross-validation of the MMPI-2 in detecting malingered posttraumatic stress disorder |journal=Journal of Personality Assessment| volume=75 |pages=449–463 |doi=10.1207/S15327752JPA7503_06}}</ref><ref name=ElhaiFp>{{cite journal|last=Elhai, J. D., Ruggiero, K. J., Frueh, B. C., Beckham, J. C., Gold, P. B., & Feldman, M. E. |title=The Infrequency-Posttraumatic Stress Disorder scale (Fptsd) for the MMPI-2: Development and initial validation with veterans presenting with combat-related PTSD |journal=Journal of Personality Assessment| volume=79 |pages=531–549 |doi=10.1207/S15327752JPA7903_08 |pmid=12511019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Elhai, J. D., Naifeh, J. A., Zucker, I. S., Gold, S. N., Deitsch, S. E., & Frueh, B. C. |title=Discriminating malingered from genuine civilian posttraumatic stress disorder: A validation of three MMPI-2 infrequency scales (F, Fp, and Fptsd) |journal=Assessment| volume=11 |pages=139–144 |doi=10.1177/1073191104264965}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Arbisi, P. A., Ben-Porath, Y. S., & McNulty, J. |title=The ability of the MMPI-2 to detect feigned PTSD within the context of compensation seeking |journal=Psychological Services| volume=3 |pages=249–261 |doi=10.1037/1541-1559.3.4.249}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Marshall, M. B., & Bagby, R. M. |title=The incremental validity and clinical utility of the MMPI-2 Infrequency Posttraumatic Stress Disorder Scale |journal=Assessment| volume=13 |pages=417–429 |doi=10.1177/1073191106290842 |pmid=17050912}}</ref><ref name=Efendov>{{cite journal|last=Efendov, A. A., Sellbom, M., & Bagby, R. M. |title=The utility and comparative incremental validity of the MMPI-2 and Trauma Symptom Inventory validity scales in the detection of feigned PTSD |journal=Psychological Assessment| volume=20 |pages=317–326 |doi=10.1037/a0013870}}</ref> Validity scales on the MMPI-2 that are reasonably accurate at detecting simulated PTSD include: The Fp scale developed by Paul Arbisi and Yosef Ben-Porath,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Arbisi, P. A., & Ben-Porath, Y. S.|title=An MMPI-2 infrequent response scale for use with psychopathological populations: The Infrequency Psychopathology scale, F(p) |journal=Psychological Assessment| volume=7 |pages=424–431 |doi=10.1037/1040-3590.7.4.424}}</ref> and the Fptsd scale developed by [[Jon Elhai]].<ref name=ElhaiFp/>

Other psychological test instruments have been investigated for PTSD malingering detection ability, but have not approached the accuracy rates of the MMPI-2. These tests include the [[Personality Assessment Inventory]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Eakin, D. E., Weathers, F. W., Benson, T. B., Anderson, C. F., & Funderbunk, B. |title=Detection of feigned posttraumatic stress disorder: A comparison of the MMPI-2 and PAI |journal=Journal of Psychopathology and Behavioral Assessment| volume=28 |pages=145–155 |doi=10.1007/s10862-005-9006-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Lange, R. T., Sullivan, K. A., & Scott, C.  |title=Comparison of MMPI-2 and PAI validity indicators to detect feigned depression and PTSD symptom reporting |journal=Psychiatry Research| volume=176 |pages=229–235 |doi=10.1016/j.psychres.2009.03.004}}</ref> and [[Trauma symptom inventory]].<ref name=Efendov/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Elhai, J. D., Gray, M. J., Naifeh, J. A., Butcher, J. J., Davis, J. L., Falsetti, S. A., & Best, C. L.  |title=Utility of the Trauma Symptom Inventory's Atypical Response Scale in detecting malingered post-traumatic stress disorder |journal=Assessment| volume=12 |pages=210–219 |doi=10.1177/1073191105275456 |pmid=15914722}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Rogers, R., Payne, J. W., Correa, A. A., Gillard, N. D., & Ross, C. A.  |title=A study of the SIRS with severely traumatized patients |journal=Journal of Personality Assessment | volume=91 |pages=429–438 |doi=10.1080/00223890903087745}}</ref>

